    "## Physics and Engineering Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "### Momentum Theory Fundamentals\n",
    "\n",
    "The aerial screw operates on momentum theory - the same principle used in modern helicopters:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$T = \\dot{m} \\cdot v = \\rho A v^2$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "- $T$ = Thrust force\n",
    "- $\\dot{m}$ = Mass flow rate of air\n",
    "- $v$ = Induced velocity through rotor disk\n",
    "- $\\rho$ = Air density\n",
    "- $A$ = Rotor disk area\n",
    "\n",
    "### Leonardo's Design Insights\n",
    "\n",
    "```{admonition} Engineering Genius\n",
    ":class: tip\n",
    "Leonardo's aerial screw demonstrates advanced understanding:\n",
    "- **Helical Surface**: Creates continuous thrust generation\n",
    "- **Large Diameter**: Maximizes air displacement efficiency\n",
    "- **Lightweight Construction**: Linen fabric minimizes structural weight\n",
    "- **Human Power**: Designed for manual operation via springs\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### Modern Validation\n",
    "\n",
    "While Leonardo's human-powered version couldn't achieve flight, his principles were sound:\n",
    "- **Scaling Laws**: Thrust increases with rotor area (diameter¬≤)\n",
    "- **Power Requirements**: Scale with thrust^(3/2) - beyond human capability\n",
    "- **Aerodynamic Efficiency**: Modern rotors achieve 60-80% efficiency\n",
    "- **Control Challenges**: Torque reaction requires tail rotor or counter-rotation"
